'''Beltinci''' ({{IPA-sl|ˈbeːltintsi|pron}}; [[Prekmurje Slovene]]: ''Böltinci'',<ref>Novak, Vilko. 2006. ''Slovar stare knjižne prekmurščine.'' Ljubljana: ZRC SAZU, p. vi.</ref> {{lang-hu|Belatinc}}<ref>Varga, Júlia. 2004. ''Magyarországi diákok a Habsburg Birodalom kisebb egyetemein és akadémiáin, 1560–1789.'' Budapest: Eötvös Loránd Tudományegyetem Levéltára, p. 129.</ref> or ''Belatincz'',<ref>''Radkersburg und Luttenberg'' (map, 1:75,000). 1914. Vienna: K.u.k. Militärgeographisches Institut.</ref> {{lang-ger|(Alt)Fellsdorf}}<ref>Engelke, Edda, & Mateja Čoh. 2011. ''"Jeder Flüchtling ist eine Schwächung der Volksdemokratie": die illegalen Überschreitungen am jugoslawisch-steirischen Grenzabschnitt in den Fünfzigerjahren.'' Vienna: Lit Verlag, p. 333.</ref>) is a town in the [[Prekmurje]] region of northeastern [[Slovenia]]. It is the seat of the [[Municipality of Beltinci]].
Until 1937, there was a [[Orthodox Judaism|Jewish Orthodox]] [[synagogue]] in Beltinci. It was built in 1860 and served the local Jewish community. On April 26, 1944, all of the Jews of the town were deported to the Auschwitz extermination camp, from which none of them returned.<ref>http://www.inv.si/psja/spomin/ebeltinc.htm</ref>
The [[parish church]] in the settlement is dedicated to [[Ladislaus I of Hungary|Saint Ladislaus]] and belongs to the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Murska Sobota]]. It dates from 1742 with late 19th-century alterations.<ref>[http://rkd.situla.org/ Slovenian Ministry of Culture register of national heritage] reference number 2871</ref>
