{{Infobox Belgium Municipality | name = Kelmis | picture = KelmisView.jpg | picture-legend = View of Kelmis | map = Kelmis Liège Belgium Map.png | map-legend = Location of Kelmis in the province of Liège | arms = BE Kelmis COA.svg | flag = Flagge Kelmis.svg | region = {{BE-REG-WAL}} | community = {{BE-DE}} | province = {{BE-PROV-LG}} | arrondissement = [[Arrondissement of Verviers|Verviers]] | nis = 63040 | pyramid-date = | 0-19 = | 20-64 = | 65 = | foreigners = | foreigners-date = | mayor = [[Louis Goebbels]] | majority = PFF | postal-codes = 4720–4728 | telephone-area = 087 | web = [http://www.kelmis.be/ www.kelmis.be] | coordinates = {{coord|50|42|N|06|00|E|region:BE|display=inline,title}} }} '''Kelmis''' ({{lang-fr|La Calamine}}) is a [[municipality]] located in the [[Belgium|Belgian]] province of [[Liège (province)|Liège]], named for the historical deposits of [[Calamine (mineral)|calamine]] ([[zinc]] ore) nearby. {{As of|2011}}, the population was 10,881; the area is {{convert|18.1|km2}} and the [[population density]] is {{convert|{{#expr:10881/18.1 round 1}}|PD/sqkm}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ng3.economie.fgov.be/ni/municipalkeyfigures/FR/slide/slide_63040.pdf#page=2 |title=Votre commune en chiffres: La&nbsp;Calamine |date=2012 |page=2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316211351/http://ng3.economie.fgov.be/ni/municipalkeyfigures/FR/slide/slide_63040.pdf#page=2 |archive-date=16 March 2016 |dead-url=no |language=fr |publisher=[[SPF Economie]] |format=PDF |df= }}</ref>
The municipality consists of the following [[deelgemeente|sub-municipalities]]: Kelmis proper, [[Hergenrath]], and [[Neu-Moresnet]].
The territory around the [[Vieille Montagne]] [[zinc]] mine in Kelmis was a neutral condominium of the Netherlands and [[Prussia]] (later Belgium and Germany) from 1816 to 1919 as [[Neutral Moresnet]], with the Mayor of Kelmis being nominated by two commissionners from the neighbouring countries. Although there were attempts by locals at making it evolve into a fully independent microstate, all of them were thwarted and it remained under double-sovereignty and neutrality until its eventual annexation by Belgium after {{nowrap|World War I}}.
In the nineteenth century a [[Low Dietsch]] dialect was spoken in Kelmis. Today Kelmis is bilingual: [[German language|German]] and [[French language|French]] and one of the nine municipalities of the [[German‑speaking Community of Belgium]].
