{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}} {{Multiple issues| {{One source|date=January 2017}} {{Refimprove|date=October 2017}}}} {{Infobox civilian attack |title = New Lodge Six shooting |partof = [[the Troubles]] |image = File:New_Lodge_rainbow.jpg |alt = |caption = A mural to the six men killed which reads "The New Lodge Six – Time for the Truth" |location = [[New Lodge, Belfast]], Northern Ireland |date = 3/4 February 1973 |time = |timezone = |type = Shooting, mass murder |weapons = [[Rifles]] |fatalities = 6 (4 civilians and 2 [[Provisional IRA]] Volunteers) |injuries = 9 |perps = [[Ulster Defence Association|UDA]], suspicion collusion }} {{Campaignbox Northern Ireland Troubles|state=collapsed}}
In the late hours of 3 February and the early hours of 4 February 1973, six men, all of whom were Catholics, were shot and killed in the [[New Lodge, Belfast|New Lodge]] area of north [[Belfast]], four (one [[Provisional IRA|IRA]] member and three civilians) of them were shot dead at the junction at Edlingham Street by [[British Army]] [[sniper]]s, the other two men were shot dead by the [[Ulster Defence Association]] (UDA). [[Irish Nationalism|Irish Nationalists]] and [[Irish Republicanism|Republicans]] believe that collusion took place between the British security forces and [[Ulster Loyalism|Loyalist paramilitaries]] in the shootings. The six men who were killed became known as "The New Lodge Six".{{fact|date=October 2017}}
==Background== [[The Troubles]] broke out in August 1969 with [[1969 Northern Ireland riots|severe rioting in Belfast]] and the British army was called in to restore order. Shortly after, the newly formed guerrilla movement the [[Provisional IRA]] waged a campaign against the British of shooting and bombing. In response, Loyalist paramilitary groups such as the [[Ulster Volunteer Force]] and [[Ulster Defence Association|(UDA)]] waged a campaign of killings against the Nationalist community in [[Northern Ireland]] and also bombed targets in the [[Republic of Ireland]]. The conflict was a bloody and bitter one with all sides carrying out massacres of civilians. The incidents included [[McGurk's Bar bombing]], which killed 15 people, was carried out by the UVF, [[Bloody Sunday (1972)|Bloody Sunday]], in which the British army shot dead 14 Catholic civilians and [[Bloody Friday (1972)|Bloody Friday]], which killed 11 civilians was carried out by the IRA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch69.htm#Aug|title=CAIN: Chronology of the Conflict 1969|first=Dr Martin|last=Melaugh|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/cgi-bin/dyndeaths.pl?querytype=date&day=4&month=12&year=1971|title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths|first=Malcolm|last=Sutton|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/events/bfriday/bf.htm|title=CAIN: Key Events - 'Bloody Friday'|first=Dr Martin|last=Melaugh|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>
The New Lodge, on the edge of the city centre, with a history of active [[Irish republicanism]] and surrounded by Loyalist areas, saw much violence during The Troubles. Most of the remaining Protestant population left under intimidation in the early 1970s, to be replaced by Catholics intimidated from Loyalist areas of Belfast. As a stronghold of the Third Battalion of the [[Provisional IRA]]'s [[Provisional IRA Belfast Brigade|Belfast Brigade]], rioting and gun battles between the IRA and the [[British Army]] and loyalist paramilitaries were almost daily occurrences during the early 1970s and other periods of high political tension such as the [[1981 Irish Hunger Strike]], and occurred sporadically during the rest of that period. The area was vulnerable to attacks by Loyalist paramilitaries throughout The Troubles, particularly to [[drive-by shooting]]s. The corner of the New Lodge Road and the Antrim Road was statistically the most dangerous spot to stand at in Northern Ireland.{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}
==Shootings== In the first four days of February 1973, fourteen people died and many more were injured in numerous gun attacks across the city. On Friday 2 February, the hooded body of 28-year-old Catholic, Patrick Bradley from [[Andersonstown]], was found in a car in Maurice Street. An 18-year-old petrol pump attendant was shot dead in his café on York Road. Earlier in the day, ten people from the [[Beechmount]] area were injured when gunmen opened fire from a passing car. Undercover British army involvement was suspected in the Beechmount shooting. In Ardoyne, in a similar attack, residents escaped injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch73.htm#Feb|title=CAIN: Chronology of the Conflict 1973|first=Dr Martin|last=Melaugh|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>
Tension was high in Belfast on Saturday 3 February. The UDA had paraded from many parts of the city to the Laddas Drive RUC station to demand the release of two of its members who had recently been interned. This was the first time Loyalists were threatened with internment and there was many protests and rioting by Loyalists in Belfast because of it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenewlodge.com/history/newlodgesix.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130043424/http://www.thenewlodge.com/history/newlodgesix.html |archivedate=30 November 2016 |df=dmy-all }} </ref>
The first shooting in the New Lodge area occurred at around 11.00pm when members of the UDA shot dead James Sloan (19) and James McCann (18) both IRA Volunteers who were shot while they stood outside Lynch's Bar, in a drive-by shooting. The car drove down the [[Antrim Road]] and fire was directed at a Chinese restaurant injuring others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/cgi-bin/dyndeaths.pl?querytype=date&day=3&month=02&year=1973|title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths|first=Malcolm|last=Sutton|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>
After the initial attack, residents gathered on the streets after hearing the shooting, they soon came under a hail of gunfire from several positions. [[British Army]] soldiers was fired a number of rounds at a crowd of people from Duncairn Gardens down Edlingham Street and from the top of Templar and Alamein Flats. For the first time in Northern Ireland the army were using their new 'Nitesights'. Four more people, Tony Campbell (19), Ambrose Hardy (26), Brendan Maguire (33) and John Loughran (35) were shot dead by British snipers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/cgi-bin/dyndeaths.pl?querytype=date&day=4&month=02&year=1973|title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths|first=Malcolm|last=Sutton|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>
==Aftermath== The British Army released a statement after the shootings in which they claimed that between 23.45 and 03.00 there was a severe gun battle in the New Lodge area.{{fact|date=October 2017}} In about 30 separate incidents, nearly 200 shots were fired at the security forces and fire was returned on most occasions. They said that seven of the people shot were gunmen and six of them died, eyewitness claims dispute these statements claiming none of those shot was armed at the time they were killed.
The sister of Ambrose Hardy claims he was waving a white petticoat when he was killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuzhound.com/articles/Irelandclick/arts2002/dec2_new_lodge_survivors.php|title=Newshound: Daily Northern Ireland news catalog - Irelandclick.com article|website=Nuzhound.com|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref> Six years later Ambrose Hardy's brother John Hardy (43) was killed by UVF gunmen while he was having dinner with his six children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/cgi-bin/dyndeaths.pl?querytype=date&day=28&month=08&year=1979|title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths|first=Malcolm|last=Sutton|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>
