{{Infobox academic|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1947|05|23}}|alma_mater=[[University of California, San Diego]]|academic_advisors=[[Margaret Langdon]]|discipline=Linguist|sub_discipline=[[Native American languages]]|workplaces=[[University of California, Los Angeles]]}}
'''Pamela Munro''' (b. May 23, 1947<ref>{{cite linked authority file|id=n84-120878|accessdate=2008-05-08}}</ref>) is an [[United States|American]] [[Linguistics|linguist]] who specializes in [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] [[Indigenous languages of the Americas|languages]]. She is distinguished research professor of linguistics at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].
She earned her Phd in 1974 from the [[University of California, San Diego]], where her graduate adviser was [[Margaret Langdon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ling.ucsd.edu/people/alumni.html#1974|title=UC San Diego - Linguistics People - Alumni|website=ling.ucsd.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref> Her dissertation, entitled ''Topics in Mojave Syntax'', was published by Garland in 1976. She has published numerous articles and books on American Indian languages,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.se/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=0,5&q=pamela+munro&btnG=|title=Google Scholar|website=scholar.google.se|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref> and was instrumental in the creation of [[dictionary|dictionaries]] for [[Zapotec language|San Lucas Quiaviní Zapotec]],<ref>{{Cite web | title = Foundation For Endangered Languages. Home | accessdate = 2012-09-02 | url = http://www.ogmios.org/ogmios_files/139.htm }}</ref> [[Chickasaw language|Chickasaw]] and [[Wolof language|Wolof]]. She is also the compiler of a series of books on college [[slang]], ''Slang U''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/keyword/pamela-munro/featured/2|title=Featured Articles about Pamela Munro - Page 2 - latimes|website=articles.latimes.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref>
